                <head>14. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On November 4, 1977, President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Jimmy
                        Carter</persName> wrote Soviet General Secretary <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLL_1">Leonid Brezhnev</persName> that Soviet anti-satellite
                        (<gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss>) testing in space had become “of
                    increasing concern to us” and had been “carefully noted in our country.”
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> warned that this concern “has
                    emerged in our efforts to build support in the U.S. Senate for a <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> agreement. This is a seriously destabilizing
                    development which we have voluntarily foregone, although we have the technical
                    capability to build systems. A very early joint agreement not to conduct further
                    tests and to forego this capability,” the President said, “would be helpful.”
                    (Letter from <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> to <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLL_1">Brezhnev</persName>, November 4; Carter Library, National
                    Security Affairs, Staff Material, Office, Outside the System File, Box 69,
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>: <persName corresp="#p_BLL_1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter
                    </persName>Correspondence: 6–12/77. <persName corresp="#p_BLL_1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName> replied that he was “ready to hold consultations” on
                        <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">ASAT</gloss> systems, but said the discussions
                    “would include, of course, all the systems and means which possess such
                    potential capability including manned space shuttles.” (Letter from <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLL_1">Brezhnev</persName> to Carter, November 15; Carter
                    Library, Plains File, President’s Personal Foreign Affairs File, Box 4, <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> (<persName corresp="#p_BLL_1"
                        >Brezhnev</persName> Drafts/Letters) 4/77–9/80)</p>
